\begin_layout Standard
Phase 3 of the 1000 Genomes Project contains approximately 2504 individuals
 with a combined total of 88 million variants.
 To test our method, we sampled 80,000 variants uniformly spaced in the
 dataset in order to limit the impact of linkage disequilibrium.
 Our method was then run on each of the 26 populations in the study as well
 as on 5 super populations and the study as a whole.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We discovered that there was great variation in the presence of cryptic
 relatedness and population structure across the 26 populations of the study.
 Under the assumptions that each study contained a homogeneous population
 of unrelated individuals, only a handful of groups contained neither large
 outliers nor heavily inflated numbers of significant results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We defined the presence of population structure as applying to those populations
 which had a greater than expected number of similarity scores below the
 mean.
 We performed a standard one-sided binomial test with 
\begin_inset Formula $p=0.5$
\end_inset

 using 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 cutoffs of 
\begin_inset Formula $.01$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $.001$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "population_table"

\end_inset

.
 Using this criterion, eight of the 26 populations met this threshold.
 Using the stricter cutoff- CLM (Colombians from Medellin, Colombia)
\begin_inset Formula $\left(p=4\times10^{-6}\right)$
\end_inset

, PUR (Puerto Ricans from Puerto Rico) 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(p=1\times10^{-11}\right)$
\end_inset

, and PEL (Peruvians from Lima, Peru) 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(p=7\times10^{-34}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Each of these populations are part of the Ad Mixed American super population
 and represent 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

new world
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 groups which have undergone extensive admixture in recent centuries.
 It is therefore reassuring that these groups of individuals would exhibit
 the greatest amount of structure among the populations surveyed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We defined the presence of cryptic relatedness as those individual pairs
 which exceed the cutoff for a family-wise error rate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=.01$
\end_inset

 and were estimated to have a coefficient of relatedness greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $.01$
\end_inset

 (for reference, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi=0.0156$
\end_inset

 corresponds to second cousins) .
 By this measure, cryptic relatedness was discovered in 6 of the 26 populations
 using this method.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The overlap in these two groups may be due to the fact that the variance
 in similarity is inflated in the presence of population structure.
 So it is not necessarily accurate to identify cryptic relatedness in this
 manner in popultations which contain structure.
 However, in populations which do not exhibit detectable structure, we still
 find many instances of related individuals in this study.
 For example, two individuals from the ACB population (African Caribbeans
 in Barbados) had a 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i,j}$
\end_inset

 score of 
\begin_inset Formula $2.6$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(p<10^{-30}\right)$
\end_inset

, whereas no other pairing exceeded the family-wise cutoff of 1.3 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(p=.0002\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Using the formula above, we estimate this relationship to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\Phi}=.0206$
\end_inset

, suggesting that those individuals are more closely related than second
 cousins.
 The closest two individuals of the same population were found in the STU
 population.
 HG03889 and HG03783 were estimated to have a kinship coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\Phi}=.252$
\end_inset

, indicating a relatedness substantially closer than second cousins.
\end_layout

